\section*{Nouns}

\paragraph{General properties}
Nouns inflect according to three genders (\textit{masculine},
\textit{feminine}, and \textit{neuter}), two
numbers (\textit{singular} and \textit{plural}), and seven cases
(\textit{nominative}, \textit{accusative}, \textit{genitive},
\textit{ablative}, \textit{dative}, \textit{locative},
and \textit{instrumental}). However, gender is a property that is inherent
to a noun. Therefore, an inflection table for a noun should have $2\times 7$
entries.

\paragraph{Case}

\paragraph{Strong and weak cases}
The seven cases can be divided into two types: the strong cases ({\Nom} and
\Acc), and the weak cases (\Gen, \Abl, \Dat, \Loc, and \Ins). There are two
main reasons for this.
\begin{enumerate}[i]
	\item For neuter nouns, the strong cases are always identical, while
		for all other nouns, the strong cases are always distinct.
		Thus, it makes sense to group the strong cases together. For
		example,

		\begin{center}
		\begin{tabular}{l|lll}
			\hline\hline
			~ & gift (\N) & man (\M) & woman (\F) \\
			\hline
			\Nom & \lan{donom} & \lan{viros} & \lan{bena} \\
			\Acc & \lan{donom} & \lan{virom} & \lan{benam} \\
			\hline\hline
		\end{tabular}
		\end{center}

	\item There are some nouns that use one stem for the strong cases, and
		a different stem for the weak cases:

		\begin{center}
		\begin{tabular}{l|lll}
			\hline\hline
			~ & thought & dog & lake \\
			\hline
			\Nom & \lan{mentis} & \lan{svon} & \lan{lokus} \\
			\Gen & \lan{manties} & \lan{sunes} & \lan{alkves} \\
			\hline\hline
		\end{tabular}
		\end{center}
\end{enumerate}


\paragraph{Inflection classes}
By examining how each noun inflects, we can come up with several broad
categories:
\begin{multicols}{2}
\begin{itemize}
	\item \textbf{I}: \lan{a}-stem nouns
	\item \textbf{II}: \lan{o}-stem nouns
	\item \textbf{III-i}: \lan{i}-stem nouns
	\item \textbf{III-u}: \lan{u}-stem nouns
	\item \textbf{III-s}: \lan{es}-stem nouns
	\item \textbf{III-n}: \lan{en}-stem nouns
	\item \textbf{III-L}: liquid-stem nouns
	\item \textbf{III-F}: fleeting \lan{s} nouns
	\item \textbf{III-C}: consonant-stem nouns
\end{itemize}
\end{multicols}

Historically, these categories have been grouped into the \textit{first
declension} (\textbf{I}), \textit{second declension} (\textbf{II}), and
\textit{third declension} (\textbf{III}). As can be seen from the list above,
the third declension contains many subcategories.

\paragraph{\lan{a}-stem nouns}

Another of the biggest classes of nouns are the \lan{a}-stems. The vast
majority of these are feminine, but there are some masculines here and there.
Some familiar examples include:
\begin{multicols}{2}
\begin{itemize}
	\item \lan{barda} (\F): beard
	\item \lan{bena} (\F): woman
	\item \lan{danva} (\F): tongue; language
	\item \lan{lana} (\F): wool
	\item \lan{luksna} (\F): moon
	\item \lan{redia} (\F): law, right
	\item \lan{pisda} (\F): vulva
	\item \lan{pletia} (\F): square, plaza
	\item \lan{pluksna} (\F): feather
	\item \lan{poina} (\F): punishment
	\item \lan{videva} (\F): widow
\end{itemize}
\end{multicols}

Since all \lan{a}-stem nouns inflect regularly, we can choose one of them to
represent them all.

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{l|ll}
	\hline\hline
	~ & \Sg & \Pl \\
	\hline
	\Nom & \lan{bena} & \lan{benai} \\
	\Acc & \lan{benam} & \lan{benans} \\
	\Gen & \lan{benas} & \lan{benóm} \\
	\Abl & \lan{benas} & \lan{benamos} \\
	\Dat & \lan{benai} & \lan{benamos} \\
	\Loc & \lan{beni} & \lan{benasu} \\
	\Ins & \lan{bene} & \lan{benafi} \\
	\hline\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\paragraph{\lan{o}-stem nouns}

One of the biggest classes of nouns are the \lan{o}-stem nouns. The vast
majority of nouns in this class are masculine and neuter, but there are a few
feminines here and there. Some familiar examples include:
\begin{multicols}{2}
\begin{itemize}
	\item \lan{adros} (\M): field
	\item \lan{Aigyptos} (\F): Egypt
	\item \lan{artos} (\M): bear
	\item \lan{divos} (\M): god
	\item \lan{donom} (\N): gift
	\item \lan{dranom} (\N): grain
	\item \lan{fumos} (\M): smoke
	\item \lan{jugom} (\N): yoke
	\item \lan{kapros} (\M): goat
	\item \lan{nefros} (\M): kidney
	\item \lan{nisdos} (\M): nest
	\item \lan{orfos} (\M): orphan; slave
	\item \lan{peplos} (\M): wheel, circle
	\item \lan{snoifos} (\M): snow
	\item \lan{svennos} (\M): sleep, slumber
	\item \lan{tauros} (\M): bull
	\item \lan{valpos} (\M): wolf
	\item \lan{verdom} (\N): word
	\item \lan{viros} (\M): man
\end{itemize}
\end{multicols}

Notice that all \lan{o}-stem neuters end in \lan{-om}, and the rest of the
\lan{o}-stems end in \lan{-os}. Since they all inflect regularly, we can
simply choose two nouns (one in \lan{-os} and one in \lan{-om}) to serve as
role models for all the \lan{o}-stems.

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{l|ll}
	\hline\hline
	~ & \Sg & \Pl \\
	\hline
	\Nom & \lan{viros} & \lan{viroi} \\
	\Acc & \lan{virom} & \lan{virons} \\
	\Gen & \lan{virosjo} & \lan{viróm} \\
	\Abl & \lan{virad} & \lan{viromos} \\
	\Dat & \lan{viroi} & \lan{viromos} \\
	\Loc & \lan{viri} & \lan{virosu} \\
	\Ins & \lan{vire} & \lan{virois} \\
	\hline\hline
\end{tabular}
\quad
\quad
\begin{tabular}{l|ll}
	\hline\hline
	~ & \Sg & \Pl \\
	\hline
	\Nom & \lan{donom} & \lan{dona} \\
	\Acc & \lan{donom} & \lan{dona} \\
	\Gen & \lan{donosjo} & \lan{donóm} \\
	\Abl & \lan{donad} & \lan{donomos} \\
	\Dat & \lan{donoi} & \lan{donomos} \\
	\Loc & \lan{doni} & \lan{donosu} \\
	\Ins & \lan{done} & \lan{donois} \\
	\hline\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}



\paragraph{\lan{i}-stem nouns}

The \lan{i}-stem nouns include both masculine and feminine nouns, and exactly
one neuter noun. Many nouns in this class have one stem for the strong cases
and another stem for the weak cases. Therefore, when listing them out on a
dictionary, it is important to list the {\Nom-\Sg} and the {\Gen-\Pl} to
represent the strong and weak stems, respectively. \footnote{These are called
the \textit{principal parts} of a noun.} If only the {\Nom-\Sg} is listed on a
dictionary entry, then we can assume that the noun doesn't change its stem.
Some familiar examples of \lan{i}-stem nouns include:
\begin{multicols}{2}
\begin{itemize}
	\item \lan{avis}\footnote{Irregular noun.} (\F): bird
	\item \lan{dotis, daties} (\F): act of giving
	\item \lan{hostis} (\M): guest
	\item \lan{mentis, manties} (\F): thought
	\item \lan{mertis, marties} (\F): death
	\item \lan{mori, maries} (\N): sea
	\item \lan{ovis, avies} (\F): sheep
	\item \lan{statis} (\F): standing; position
	\item \lan{vestis, usties} (\F): clothing
\end{itemize}
\end{multicols}

Since the vast majority of \lan{i}-stem nouns are regular \footnote{A noun
that has one stem for the strong cases and another stem for the weak cases is
still considered regular, because its inflection table can be inferred from
just two principal parts: the {\Nom-\Sg} and the {\Gen-\Sg}.}, we can just
choose one word to represent all regular nouns in this class, and then treat
the irregular nouns separately.

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{l|ll}
	\hline\hline
	~ & \Sg & \Pl \\
	\hline
	\Nom & \lan{hostis} & \lan{hostes} \\
	\Acc & \lan{hostim} & \lan{hostins} \\
	\Gen & \lan{hosties} & \lan{hostióm} \\
	\Abl & \lan{hosties} & \lan{hostimos} \\
	\Dat & \lan{hostiei} & \lan{hostimos} \\
	\Loc & \lan{hosti} & \lan{hostisu} \\
	\Ins & \lan{hostie} & \lan{hostifi} \\
	\hline\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

The only neuter \lan{i}-stem noun is \lan{mori}, and it's completely regular,
albeit with a change of stem.

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{l|ll}
	\hline\hline
	~ & \Sg & \Pl \\
	\hline
	\Nom & \lan{mori} & \lan{moria} \\
	\Acc & \lan{mori} & \lan{moria} \\
	\Gen & \lan{maries} & \lan{marióm} \\
	\Abl & \lan{maries} & \lan{marimos} \\
	\Dat & \lan{mariei} & \lan{marimos} \\
	\Loc & \lan{mari} & \lan{marisu} \\
	\Ins & \lan{marie} & \lan{marifi} \\
	\hline\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

One notable irregular noun is \lan{avis}. It is considered irregular because it
has three distinct stems, instead of the usual one or two. Moreover, since one
of the stems is purely vocalic, an epenthetic consonant is sometimes inserted
between the stem and the ending. The inflection table is shown below.

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{l|ll}
	\hline\hline
	~ & \Sg & \Pl \\
	\hline
	\Nom & \lan{avis} & \lan{aves} \\
	\Acc & \lan{avim} & \lan{avins} \\
	\Gen & \lan{ujes} & \lan{ujóm} \\
	\Abl & \lan{ujes} & \lan{vimos} \\
	\Dat & \lan{ujei} & \lan{vimos} \\
	\Loc & \lan{uvi} & \lan{visu} \\
	\Ins & \lan{uje} & \lan{vifi} \\
	\hline\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

The inflection tables for all irregular nouns can be found in section
\ref{sec:irregular-nouns}.

\paragraph{\lan{u}-stem nouns}

The \lan{u}-stem nouns include nouns from all three genders. Since this class
is a relic from PIE, there are relatively many irregular nouns here. Some
familiar examples include:
\begin{multicols}{2}
\begin{itemize}
	\item \lan{befrus} (\M): beaver
	\item \lan{brus}\footnote{Irregular noun.} (\F): eyebrow
	\item \lan{dakru} (\N): tear (of the eye)
	\item \lan{danu}\footnotemark[\value{footnote}] (\N): river
	\item \lan{denus}\footnotemark[\value{footnote}] (\F): jaw; cheek
	\item \lan{djus}\footnotemark[\value{footnote}] (\M): sky, heaven
	\item \lan{doru}\footnotemark[\value{footnote}] (\N): tree
	\item \lan{dustus} (\M): taste
	\item \lan{lokus, alkues} (\M): pond, lake
	\item \lan{naus, naves} (\F): boat, ship
	\item \lan{smerus, smarues} (\M): grease
	\item \lan{sunus} (\M): son
\end{itemize}
\end{multicols}

We can choose two of these to represent the regular \lan{u}-stem nouns: one for
the masculine and feminine nouns, and one for the neuters.

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{l|ll}
	\hline\hline
	~ & \Sg & \Pl \\
	\hline
	\Nom & \lan{sunus} & \lan{sunús} \\
	\Acc & \lan{sunum} & \lan{sununs} \\
	\Gen & \lan{sunues} & \lan{sunuóm} \\
	\Abl & \lan{sunues} & \lan{sunumos} \\
	\Dat & \lan{sunuei} & \lan{sunumos} \\
	\Loc & \lan{sunui} & \lan{sunusu} \\
	\Ins & \lan{sunue} & \lan{sunufi} \\
	\hline\hline
\end{tabular}
\quad\quad
	\begin{tabular}{l|ll}
	\hline\hline
	~ & \Sg & \Pl \\
	\hline
	\Nom & \lan{danu} & \lan{danú} \\
	\Acc & \lan{danu} & \lan{danú} \\
	\Gen & \lan{danues} & \lan{danuóm} \\
	\Abl & \lan{danues} & \lan{danumos} \\
	\Dat & \lan{danuei} & \lan{danumos} \\
	\Loc & \lan{danui} & \lan{danusu} \\
	\Ins & \lan{danue} & \lan{danufi} \\
	\hline\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

All the irregular nouns can be found in the tables under section
\ref{sec:irregular-nouns}.

\paragraph{\lan{es}-stem nouns}

The class of \lan{es}-stem nouns includes all three genders. All of these nouns
are regular. Some familiar examples are:
\begin{multicols}{2}
\begin{itemize}
	\item \lan{ankos} (\N): curve, bend
	\item \lan{denos} (\N): race, lineage
	\item \lan{jugos} (\N): pair of yoked animals
	\item \lan{menos} (\N): mind
	\item \lan{nefos} (\N): cloud
	\item \lan{odés} (\M): axe, hatchet
	\item \lan{pletos} (\N): breadth
	\item \lan{rebos} (\N): darkness
	\item \lan{slevos} (\N): fame; glory
	\item \lan{tenos} (\N): extension
\end{itemize}
\end{multicols}

Since all \lan{es}-stem nouns are regular, we can simply choose two nouns
to represent them all: one for the masculine and feminine nouns, and one for
the neuters.

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{l|ll}
	\hline\hline
	~ & \Sg & \Pl \\
	\hline
	\Nom & \lan{odés} & \lan{odeses} \\
	\Acc & \lan{odesam} & \lan{odesans} \\
	\Gen & \lan{odesos} & \lan{odesóm} \\
	\Abl & \lan{odesos} & \lan{odesmos} \\
	\Dat & \lan{odesei} & \lan{odesmos} \\
	\Loc & \lan{odesi} & \lan{odesu} \\
	\Ins & \lan{odese} & \lan{odesfi} \\
	\hline\hline
\end{tabular}
\quad\quad
\begin{tabular}{l|ll}
	\hline\hline
	~ & \Sg & \Pl \\
	\hline
	\Nom & \lan{menos} & \lan{menós} \\
	\Acc & \lan{menos} & \lan{menós} \\
	\Gen & \lan{menesos} & \lan{menesóm} \\
	\Abl & \lan{menesos} & \lan{menesmos} \\
	\Dat & \lan{menesei} & \lan{menesmos} \\
	\Loc & \lan{menesi} & \lan{menesu} \\
	\Ins & \lan{menese} & \lan{menesfi} \\
	\hline\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\paragraph{\lan{en}-stem nouns}

The \lan{en}-stem nouns are all neuter, and most of them are regular. Some
common examples are:
\begin{multicols}{2}
\begin{itemize}
	\item \lan{denaman, danamens} (\N): offspring; generation (genealogical)
	\item \lan{noman, nemens} (\N): name
	\item \lan{numan, panvamens} (\N): spirit, soul
	\item \lan{petan, patens} (\N): wing
	\item \lan{seman, samens} (\N): seed
	\item \lan{sovan, savens} (\N): sun
	\item \lan{terman, tarmens} (\N): boundary; end
	\item \lan{vodan, vedens} (\N): water
	\item \lan{vosan}\footnote{Irregular noun.} (\N): spring (season)
\end{itemize}
\end{multicols}

\paragraph{Liquid-stem nouns}

The liquid consonants are \lan{l} and \lan{r}. If the {\Nom-\Sg} of a noun ends
in a liquid consonant, then it belongs to the class of liquid-stem nouns. This
class includes both masculine and feminine nouns. Some familiar examples are:
\begin{multicols}{2}
\begin{itemize}
	\item \lan{abol}\footnotemark[\value{footnote}] (\M): apple
	\item \lan{bor}\footnotemark[\value{footnote}] (\M): thief
	\item \lan{brater} (\M): brother
	\item \lan{denator, danatres} (\M): parent
	\item \lan{dotor, datres} (\M): giver
	\item \lan{fugater, fugtres} (\F): daughter
	\item \lan{for, fures} (\M): door
	\item \lan{mater} (\F): mother
	\item \lan{pater} (\M): father
	\item \lan{sper, aspres} (\M): sparrow
	\item \lan{ster, astres} (\M): star
	\item \lan{svesor}\footnotemark[\value{footnote}] (\F): sister
	\item \lan{vistor} (\M): witness
\end{itemize}
\end{multicols}

The vowel right before the liquid is usually elided in all its forms except
the {\Nom-\Sg},
like \lan{pater} > \lan{patres}, or \lan{abol} > \lan{ables}. However, if
the {\Nom-\Sg} is a monosyllable, then no elision occurs, e.g.
\lan{bor} > \lan{bores}. With this rule in mind, we can choose one of the
liquid-stem nouns to serve as a role model for the rest.

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{l|ll}
	\Nom & \lan{pater} & \lan{patres} \\
	\Acc & \lan{patram} & \lan{patrans} \\
	\Gen & \lan{patres} & \lan{patróm} \\
	\Abl & \lan{patres} & \lan{patrimos} \\
	\Dat & \lan{patrei} & \lan{patrimos} \\
	\Loc & \lan{patri} & \lan{patrisu} \\
	\Ins & \lan{patre} & \lan{patrifi} \\
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\paragraph{Fleeting \lan{s} nouns}

There are some nouns that end in \lan{-s} in the {\Nom-\Sg}, but this \lan{-s}
gets dropped in all other inflections. This is called the fleeting \lan{s}.
Some nouns like this include:
\begin{multicols}{2}
\begin{itemize}
	\item \lan{anats} (\F): duck
	\item \lan{donts, dantes} (\M): tooth
	\item \lan{fans} (\F): goose
	\item \lan{frags} (\M): dregs, sediment (of wine, oil, fat)
	\item \lan{nogs, neges} (\M): nail (of the finger or toe)
	\item \lan{oms, ames} (\M): shoulder
	\item \lan{ops} (\N): eye
	\item \lan{ponts, pantes} (\M): path
	\item \lan{rads} (\F): root
	\item \lan{reds} (\M): king
	\item \lan{sals} (\M): salt
	\item \lan{vents, vantes} (\M): wind
	\item \lan{vops} (\F): voice, speech
\end{itemize}
\end{multicols}

\paragraph{Consonant-stem nouns}

If a noun doesn't fall into any of the categories mentioned above, then we can
usually take the stem and just append the inflectional endings directly to it.
Some nouns that don't fall into the previous classes include:
\begin{multicols}{2}
\begin{itemize}
	\item \lan{dom, dems} (\M): house, home
	\item \lan{famón}\footnote{Irregular noun.} (\M): earthling
	\item \lan{fedóm, fames} (\F): earth
	\item \lan{fejóm, fimes} (\F): winter
	\item \lan{frags} (\M): dregs, sediment (of wine, oil, fat)
	\item \lan{gerán}\footnotemark[\value{footnote}] (\M): crane, heron
\end{itemize}
\end{multicols}

